{"title_page": "HMS Strombolo (1797)", "text_new": "{{other ships|Leander (ship)|HMS Strombolo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{| {{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = \n| Ship caption = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n|Ship country=Great Britain\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Kingdom of Great Britain|civil}}\n| Ship name = ''Leander''\n| Ship namesake = \n| Ship owner =\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship builder = Thomas Hearn, North Shields<ref>[http://www.tynebuiltships.co.uk/ShipsL.html Tyne Built Ships: ''Leander''.]</ref>\n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship commissioned = \n| Ship decommissioned = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship renamed = \n| Ship captured = \n| Ship fate = Sold 1797\n| Ship status = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Great Britain\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Kingdom of Great Britain|naval}}\n| Ship name = \n| Ship namesake = \n| Ship owner =\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship builder = \n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched = \n| Ship acquired = April 1797 by purchase\n| Ship commissioned = \n| Ship decommissioned = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship renamed = \n| Ship captured = \n| Ship fate = Broken up 1809\n| Ship status = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption ={{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=374}}\n| Ship class = [[Bomb vessel|Bomb-vessel]]\n| Ship tons burthen=323{{small|{{frac|64|94}}}} ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]])\n| Ship length =*Overall:{{cvt|92|ft|5|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n*Keel:{{cvt|75|ft|3|in|m|1|abbr=on}} \n| Ship beam = {{cvt|28|ft|5+1/4|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = \n| Ship hold depth = {{cvt|12|ft|6+1/2|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| Ship propulsion = \n| Ship sail plan = \n| Ship complement =67\n| Ship armament =*Upper deck:4 \u00d7 68-pounder [[carronades]]\n*[[Quarter deck|QD]]:4 \u00d7 18-pounder carronades\n*[[Forecastle|Fc]]:2 \u00d7 18-pounder carronades\n*Mortars:2 \u00d7 10-inch\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n''' HMS'' Strombolo''''' was launched in 1795 at North Shields as the mercantile ''Leander''. The [[Royal Navy]] purchased her in 1797, converted her to a [[Bomb vessel|bomb-vessel]], and renamed her. She participated in the capture of Malta in 1800. The Navy laid her up in 1802 and had her [[ship breaking|broken up]] in 1809. \n\n==Royal Navy==\n''Strombolo'' was commissioned in August 1797 under Commander John Broughton.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=374}}\n\nHowever, the bomb-vessel ''Strombolo'' was reported already to have participated in a bombardment of Cadiz on 5 July 1797. British casualties were light, with none of the three bomb vessels suffering any.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=29 July 1797|issue=14032|page=717}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 November 1798 {{HMS|Santa Dorothea|1798|6}}, operating in company with {{HMS|Perseus|1776|6}}, ''Strombolo'', and {{HMS|Bulldog|1782|6}} captured the 16-gun Spanish Navy brig ''San Leon'' on the [[Lisbon]] station. She was armed with sixteen 6-pounder guns and had a crew of 82 men.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=12 February 1799|issue=15107|page=148}}</ref>\n\nShe sailed for the Mediterranean in October 1799. \n\nIn the [[action of 31 March 1800]], a British squadron consisting of the ships of the line {{HMS|Foudroyant|1798|2}} and {{HMS|Lion|1777|2}}, [[frigate]] {{HMS|Penelope|1798|2}}, brigs [[French brig Alerte (1787)|''Minorca'']] and {{HMS|Vincejo|1799|2}}, and [[bomb vessel]] {{HMS|Strombolo|1797|2}} captured the French ship of the line [[French ship Guillaume Tell (1795)|''Guillaume Tell'']]. Although all six vessels of the British squadron shared the prize money,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15474|page=421|date=24 April 1802}}</ref> only the two ships of the line and the frigate actually engaged in the battle.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15263|pages=575\u2013576|date=31 May 1800}}</ref>\n\nBecause she was part of the British squadron supporting the capture of Malta, ''Strombolo'' shared in the prize money for the capture on 30 March 1800 of [[HMS Malta (1800)|''Guilaume Tell'']].<ref>{{London Gazette|date=24 April 1802|issue=15474|page=421}}</ref>\n\nIn May ''Strombolo'' was present at the capture of Malta.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=7 October 1800|issue=15300|page=1153}}</ref> \n\nOn 25 June, {{HMS|Success|1781|2}} captured the French [[aviso]] ''Intreprenante'' (or ''Entreprenante''). The next day ''Success'' captured another aviso, ''Redoutable'', with the same armament, establishment, and mission as ''Intreprenante''.<ref name=LG15301>{{London Gazette|issue=15301|pages=1170\u20131171|date=11 October 1800}}</ref> Unfortunately for ''Success'', she had to share the prize money with a large number of other British warships, including ''Strombolo''.{{refn|A first-class share of the headmoney was [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]4 11[[shilling|s]] 2[[pence|d]]; a fifth-class share was worth 6d. Because ''Success'' and ''Vincejo'', among others, had been overpaid on the prize money for the two French vessels' hulls and cargoes, \u00a32 13s 8d for a first-class share and 3d for a fifth-class share were deducted from this payment.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15499|page=769|date=20 July 1802}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nThe French frigates {{ship|French frigate|Diane|1796|2}} (or ''Dianne'') and {{ship|French frigate|Justice|1794|2}} escaped from [[Valletta]] Harbour on 24 August. {{HMS|Success|1781|2}}, {{HMS|Northumberland|1798|2}}, and [[French ship G\u00e9n\u00e9reux (1785)|''Genereux'']] captured ''Diane'', which the British took into service as HMS ''Niobe'', but ''Justice'' escaped.<ref>{{London Gazette|pages=1156\u20131157|issue=15300|date=7 October 1800}}</ref> As part of the blockading squadron, ''Strombolo'' shared in the prize money for ''Diane''.<ref>{{London Gazette|page=822|issue=15503|date=3 August 1802}}</ref>{{refn|The British captured ''Justice'' at the [[Siege of Alexandria|fall of Alexandria]] on 2 September 1801; in the division of the spoils, the Ottoman navy received ''Justice''.<ref>{{London Gazette|page=1354|issue=15426|date=10 November 1801}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nMalta surrendered on 5 September. ''Strombolo'' was among the many vessels and Army units that shared the prize money.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=26 July 1803|issue=15605|pages=929\u2013930}}</ref>\n\n''Strombolo'' received a share of the prize money for the transport ''Venus'', wrecked off [[Minorca]] and salvaged on 20 October with the aid of the frigate {{HMS|Pearl|1762|6}}, 18-gun sloop ''Lutine'', ''Strombolo'', and the 6-gun tender {{HMS|Alexander|1796|2}}. On 31 October, ''Pearl'' with ''Lutine'', ''Strombolo'', the 20-gun corvette {{HMS|Bonne Citoyenne|1796|2}}, and the 12-gun polacca ''Transfer'', took transport ''Fowler'' from [[Port Mahon]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15534|page=1228|date=20 November 1802}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16017|page=441|date=7 April 1807}}</ref> \n\nIn January 1801 Commander Anthony Thompson replaced Broughton. In May Commander Edward Brown replaced Thompson.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=374}}\n''Strombolo'' returned to Portsmouth on 3 June 1802 and was laid up at Deptford.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=374}}\n\n==Fate==\n''Strombolo'' was broken up in [[Deptford Dockyard]] July 1809.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=374}}\n\n==Notes, citations, and references==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n'''References'''\n* {{cite book |first=Rif|last=Winfield|title=British Warships in the Age of Sail 1793\u20131817: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates|publisher=Seaforth Publishing|year=2008|isbn=1-86176-246-1|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:1797 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Tyne]]\n[[Category:Age of Sail merchant ships of England]]\n[[Category:Bomb vessels of the Royal Navy]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|Leander (ship)|HMS Strombolo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{| {{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = \n| Ship caption = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n|Ship country=Great Britain\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Kingdom of Great Britain|civil}}\n| Ship name = ''Leander''\n| Ship namesake = \n| Ship owner =\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship builder = Thomas Hearn, North Shields<ref>[http://www.tynebuiltships.co.uk/ShipsL.html Tyne Built Ships: ''Leander''.]</ref>\n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship commissioned = \n| Ship decommissioned = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship renamed = \n| Ship captured = \n| Ship fate = Sold 1797\n| Ship status = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=title\n|Ship country=Great Britain\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Kingdom of Great Britain|naval}}\n| Ship name = \n| Ship namesake = \n| Ship owner =\n| Ship operator = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship builder = \n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship laid down = \n| Ship launched = \n| Ship acquired = April 1797 by purchase\n| Ship commissioned = \n| Ship decommissioned = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship renamed = \n| Ship captured = \n| Ship fate = Broken up 1809\n| Ship status = \n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption ={{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=374}}\n| Ship class = [[Bomb vessel|Bomb-vessel]]\n| Ship tons burthen=323{{small|{{frac|64|94}}}} ([[Builder's Old Measurement|bm]])\n| Ship length =*Overall:{{cvt|92|ft|5|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n*Keel:{{cvt|75|ft|3|in|m|1|abbr=on}} \n| Ship beam = {{cvt|28|ft|5+1/4|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = \n| Ship hold depth = {{cvt|12|ft|6+1/2|in|m|1|abbr=on}}\n| Ship propulsion = \n| Ship sail plan = \n| Ship complement =67\n| Ship armament =*Upper deck:4 \u00d7 68-pounder [[carronades]]\n*[[Quarter deck|QD]]:4 \u00d7 18-pounder carronades\n*[[Forecastle|Fc]]:2 \u00d7 18-pounder carronades\n*Mortars:2 \u00d7 10-inch\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n''' HMS'' Strombolo''''' was launched in 1795 at North Shields as the mercantile ''Leander''. The [[Royal Navy]] purchased her in 1797, converted her to a [[Bomb vessel|bomb-vessel]], and renamed her. She participated in the capture of Malta in 1800. The Navy laid her up in 1802 and had her [[ship breaking|broken up]] in 1809. \n\n==Royal Navy==\n''Strombolo'' was commissioned in August 1797 under Commander John Broughton.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=374}}\n\nHowever, the bomb-vessel ''Strombolo'' was reported already to have participated in a bombardment of Cadiz on 5 July 1797. British casualties were light, with none of the three bomb vessels suffering any.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=29 July 1797|issue=14032|page=717}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 November 1798 {{HMS|Santa Dorothea|1798|6}}, operating in company with {{HMS|Perseus|1776|6}}, ''Strombolo'', and {{HMS|Bulldog|1782|6}} captured the 16-gun Spanish Navy brig ''San Leon'' on the [[Lisbon]] station. She was armed with sixteen 6-pounder guns and had a crew of 82 men.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=12 February 1799|issue=15107|page=148}}</ref>\n\nShe sailed for the Mediterranean in October 1799. \n\nIn the [[action of 31 March 1800]], a British squadron consisting of the ships of the line {{HMS|Foudroyant|1798|2}} and {{HMS|Lion|1777|2}}, [[frigate]] {{HMS|Penelope|1798|2}}, brigs [[French brig Alerte (1787)|''Minorca'']] and {{HMS|Vincejo|1799|2}}, and [[bomb vessel]] {{HMS|Strombolo|1797|2}} captured the French ship of the line [[French ship Guillaume Tell (1795)|''Guillaume Tell'']]. Although all six vessels of the British squadron shared the prize money,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15474|page=421|date=24 April 1802}}</ref> only the two ships of the line and the frigate actually engaged in the battle.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15263|pages=575\u2013576|date=31 May 1800}}</ref>\n\nBecause she was part of the British squadron supporting the capture of Malta, ''Strombolo'' shared in the prize money for the capture on 30 March 1800 of [[HMS Malta (1800)|''Guilaume Tell'']].<ref>{{London Gazette|date=24 April 1802|issue=15474|page=421}}</ref>\n\nIn May ''Strombolo'' was present at the capture of Malta.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=7 October 1800|issue=15300|page=1153}}</ref> \n\nOn 25 June, {{HMS|Success|1781|2}} captured the French [[aviso]] ''Intreprenante'' (or ''Entreprenante''). The next day ''Success'' captured another aviso, ''Redoutable'', with the same armament, establishment, and mission as ''Intreprenante''.<ref name=LG15301>{{London Gazette|issue=15301|pages=1170\u20131171|date=11 October 1800}}</ref> Unfortunately for ''Success'', she had to share the prize money with a large number of other British warships, including ''Strombolo''.{{refn|A first-class share of the headmoney was [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]4 11[[shilling|s]] 2[[pence|d]]; a fifth-class share was worth 6d. Because ''Success'' and ''Vincejo'', among others, had been overpaid on the prize money for the two French vessels' hulls and cargoes, \u00a32 13s 8d for a first-class share and 3d for a fifth-class share were deducted from this payment.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15499|page=769|date=20 July 1802}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nThe French frigates {{ship|French frigate|Diane|1796|2}} (or ''Dianne'') and {{ship|French frigate|Justice|1794|2}} escaped from [[Valletta]] Harbour on 24 August. {{HMS|Success|1781|2}}, {{HMS|Northumberland|1798|2}}, and [[French ship G\u00e9n\u00e9reux (1785)|''Genereux'']] captured ''Diane'', which the British took into service as HMS ''Niobe'', but ''Justice'' escaped.<ref>{{London Gazette|pages=1156\u20131157|issue=15300|date=7 October 1800}}</ref> As part of the blockading squadron, ''Strombolo'' shared in the prize money for ''Diane''.<ref>{{London Gazette|page=822|issue=15503|date=3 August 1802}}</ref>{{refn|The British captured ''Justice'' at the [[Siege of Alexandria|fall of Alexandria]] on 2 September 1801; in the division of the spoils, the Ottoman navy received ''Justice''.<ref>{{London Gazette|page=1354|issue=15426|date=10 November 1801}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n\nMalta surrendered on 5 September. ''Strombolo'' was among the many vessels and Army units that shared the prize money.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=26 July 1803|issue=15605|pages=929\u2013930}}</ref>\n\n''Strombolo'' received a share of the prize money for the transport ''Venus'', wrecked off [[Minorca]] and salvaged on 20 October with the aid of the frigate {{HMS|Pearl|1762|6}}, 18-gun sloop ''Lutine'', ''Strombolo'', and the 6-gun tender {{HMS|Alexander|1796|2}}. On 31 October, ''Pearl'' with ''Lutine'', ''Strombolo'', the 20-gun corvette {{HMS|Bonne Citoyenne|1796|2}}, and the 12-gun polacca ''Transfer'', took transport ''Fowler'' from [[Port Mahon]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=15534|page=1228|date=20 November 1802}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16017|page=441|date=7 April 1807}}</ref> \n\nIn January 1801 Commander Anthony Thompson replaced Broughton. In May Commander Edward Brown replaced Thompson.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=374}}\n''Strombolo'' returned to Portsmouth on 3 June 1802 and was laid up at Deptford.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=374}}\n\n==Fate==\n''Strombolo'' was broken up in July 1809.{{sfnp|Winfield|2008|p=374}} \n\n==Notes, citations, and references==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist|30em}}\n'''References'''\n* {{cite book |first=Rif|last=Winfield|title=British Warships in the Age of Sail 1793\u20131817: Design, Construction, Careers and Fates|publisher=Seaforth Publishing|year=2008|isbn=1-86176-246-1|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:1797 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Tyne]]\n[[Category:Age of Sail merchant ships of England]]\n[[Category:Bomb vessels of the Royal Navy]]\n", "name_user": "Liandrei", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFate:+location", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Strombolo_(1797)"}
{"title_page": "FC Slutsk", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname   = Slutsk\n| image      = Fc-slutsk-logo.png\n| fullname   = Athletic Football Club Slutsk<ref>{{cite web|title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \"\u0421\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\"|url=http://sfc-slutsk.by/About|website=Sfc-slutsk.by|publisher=\u0421\u0424\u041a \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\"|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n| nickname   = \n| shortname  = \n| founded    = 1998\n| dissolved  = \n| ground     = [[City Stadium (Slutsk)|City Stadium]], [[Slutsk]]\n| capacity   = 1,896\n| chrtitle   = Chairman\n| chairman   = Oleg Karanevsky\n| mgrtitle   = Head Coach\n| manager    = [[Vitaliy Pavlov (footballer, born 1965)|Vitaliy Pavlov]]\n| league     = [[Belarusian Premier League]]\n| season     = [[2019 Belarusian Premier League|2019]]\n| position   = 11th\n| website    = http://sfc-slutsk.by\n| pattern_la1 = _eastern18h\n| pattern_b1  = _eastern18h\n| pattern_ra1 = _eastern18h\n| pattern_sh1 = _adidaswhite\n| pattern_so1 = _3_stripes_white\n| leftarm1    = 0000FF\n| body1       = 0000FF\n| rightarm1   = 0000FF\n| shorts1     = 0000FF\n| socks1      = 0000FF\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = _unterhaching1819t\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body2       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts2     = FFFFFF\n| socks2      = FFFFFF\n}}\n\n'''FC Slutsk''' ({{lang-be|\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a}}; {{lang-ru|\u0421\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a}}) is a [[Belarus]]ian football club based in [[Slutsk]], [[Minsk Oblast]].\n\n==History==\nThe team was founded in 1998 as '''Slutsksakhar Slutsk'''. Between 1998 and 2007 they played in Minsk Oblast championship.\nIn 2008, they joined [[Belarusian Second League]]. In 2010, they finished in second place and were granted a promotion to [[Belarusian First League|First League]] in 2011. In early 2011 the team changed its name to '''Slutsk'''.\n\n==Online Popularity==\nIn early 2020, FC Slutsk became subject to an influx of international support. This was a result of the cancellation of various football leagues during the outbreak of Coronavirus COVID-19. Whilst the Belarusian Premier League continued, football fans around the world flocked to watch the only available games. The creation of Facebook group 'FK Slutsk Worldwide', originating from Australia, excelled this popularity and resulted in FC Slutsk striker Artem Serdyuk joining the page.\n\n==Current squad==\n''As of March 2020 ''<ref>[http://sfc-slutsk.by/club/teams/main FC Slutsk squad]</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|name=[[Vitali Trubila]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|name=[[Yuriy Teterenko]]|nat=UKR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|name=[[Yegor Semenov]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no=9|name=[[Artyom Serdyuk]]|nat=RUS|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|name=[[Soslan Takulov]]|nat=RUS|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|name=[[Vladislav Sychev]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|name=[[Pavel Zuyevich]]|nat=BLR|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|name=[[Umar Bala Mohammed]]|nat=NGA|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|name=[[Souleymane Koanda]]|nat=BFA|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|name=[[Dzyanis Obrazaw]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|name=[[Yevgeniy Velko]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|name=[[Igor Bobko]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|name=[[Yury Kazlow]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|name=[[Serhiy Chebotayev]]|nat=UKR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=30|name=[[Ilya Branovets]]|nat=BLR|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=34|name=[[Barys Pankrataw]]|nat=BLR|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=55|name=[[Alyaksandr Anyukevich]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=59|name=[[Roman Krivulkin]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=71|name=[[Marat Burayev]]|nat=RUS|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=77|name=[[Alan Koroyev]]|nat=RUS|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=78|name=[[Abdoul Gafar Sirima]]|nat=BFA|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=99|name=[[Dramane Salou]]|nat=BFA|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==League and Cup history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!width=55|Season\n!width=50|{{Tooltip|Level|League level}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|Pos|Position}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=60|Goals\n!width=45|Points\n![[Belarusian Cup|Domestic Cup]]\n!Notes\n|-\n| 2008 ||style=\"background:#A3E9FF\"| 3rd || '''5''' || 30 || 15 || 6 || 9 || 53\u201337 || '''51''' || || \n|-\n| 2009 ||style=\"background:#A3E9FF\"| 3rd || '''4''' || 26 || 14 || 3 || 9 || 48\u201337 || '''45''' ||Round of 64 || \n|-\n| 2010 ||style=\"background:#A3E9FF\"| 3rd || '''2''' || 34 || 25 || 6 || 3 || 79\u201330 || '''81''' ||Round of 32 || Promoted\n|-\n| 2011 ||style=\"background:#D0F0C0\"| 2nd || '''5''' || 30 || 13 || 10 || 7 || 44\u201333 || '''49''' ||Round of 32  || \n|-\n| 2012 ||style=\"background:#D0F0C0\"| 2nd || '''5''' || 28 || 15 || 7 || 6 || 59\u201327 || '''52''' ||Round of 32  ||\n|-\n| 2013 ||style=\"background:#D0F0C0\"| 2nd || '''1''' || 30 || 19 || 9 || 2 || 54\u201319 || '''66''' ||Round of 32  || Promoted\n|-\n| 2014 || 1st || '''9''' || 32 || 11 || 7 || 14 || 26\u201334 || '''40''' ||Round of 16  ||\n|-\n| 2015 || 1st || '''11''' || 26 || 6 || 7 || 13 || 26-30 || '''25''' ||Round of 16  ||\n|-\n| 2016 || 1st || '''12''' || 30 || 6 || 12 || 12 || 22-34 || '''30''' || Quarter-finals ||\n|-\n| 2017 || 1st || '''8''' || 30 || 12 || 8 || 10 || 30-34 || '''44''' || Quarter-finals  ||\n|}\n\n==Managers==\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Yuriy Krot]] (2005\u201315)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Vyachaslaw Hryharaw]] (2015\u20132016)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Vitaliy Pavlov (footballer, born 1965)|Vitaliy Pavlov]] (2017\u2013)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sfc-slutsk.by/  Official Website] {{in lang|ru}}\n\n{{Belarusian Premier League teamlist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Slutsk}}\n[[Category:Football clubs in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Sport in Minsk Region]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1998]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname   = Slutsk\n| image      = Fc-slutsk-logo.png\n| fullname   = Athletic Football Club Slutsk<ref>{{cite web|title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \"\u0421\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\"|url=http://sfc-slutsk.by/About|website=Sfc-slutsk.by|publisher=\u0421\u0424\u041a \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\"|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n| nickname   = \n| shortname  = \n| founded    = 1998\n| dissolved  = \n| ground     = [[City Stadium (Slutsk)|City Stadium]], [[Slutsk]]\n| capacity   = 1,896\n| chrtitle   = Chairman\n| chairman   = Oleg Karanevsky\n| mgrtitle   = Head Coach\n| manager    = [[Vitaliy Pavlov (footballer, born 1965)|Vitaliy Pavlov]]\n| league     = [[Belarusian Premier League]]\n| season     = [[2019 Belarusian Premier League|2019]]\n| position   = 11th\n| website    = http://sfc-slutsk.by\n| pattern_la1 = _eastern18h\n| pattern_b1  = _eastern18h\n| pattern_ra1 = _eastern18h\n| pattern_sh1 = _adidaswhite\n| pattern_so1 = _3_stripes_white\n| leftarm1    = 0000FF\n| body1       = 0000FF\n| rightarm1   = 0000FF\n| shorts1     = 0000FF\n| socks1      = 0000FF\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = _unterhaching1819t\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body2       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts2     = FFFFFF\n| socks2      = FFFFFF\n}}\n\n'''FC Slutsk''' ({{lang-be|\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a}}; {{lang-ru|\u0421\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a}}) is a [[Belarus]]ian football club based in [[Slutsk]], [[Minsk Oblast]].\n\n==History==\nThe team was founded in 1998 as '''Slutsksakhar Slutsk'''. Between 1998 and 2007 they played in Minsk Oblast championship.\nIn 2008, they joined [[Belarusian Second League]]. In 2010, they finished in second place and were granted a promotion to [[Belarusian First League|First League]] in 2011. In early 2011 the team changed its name to '''Slutsk'''.\n\n==Current squad==\n''As of March 2020 ''<ref>[http://sfc-slutsk.by/club/teams/main FC Slutsk squad]</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|name=[[Vitali Trubila]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|name=[[Yuriy Teterenko]]|nat=UKR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|name=[[Yegor Semenov]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no=9|name=[[Artyom Serdyuk]]|nat=RUS|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|name=[[Soslan Takulov]]|nat=RUS|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|name=[[Vladislav Sychev]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|name=[[Pavel Zuyevich]]|nat=BLR|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|name=[[Umar Bala Mohammed]]|nat=NGA|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|name=[[Souleymane Koanda]]|nat=BFA|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|name=[[Dzyanis Obrazaw]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|name=[[Yevgeniy Velko]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|name=[[Igor Bobko]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|name=[[Yury Kazlow]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|name=[[Serhiy Chebotayev]]|nat=UKR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=30|name=[[Ilya Branovets]]|nat=BLR|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=34|name=[[Barys Pankrataw]]|nat=BLR|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=55|name=[[Alyaksandr Anyukevich]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=59|name=[[Roman Krivulkin]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=71|name=[[Marat Burayev]]|nat=RUS|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=77|name=[[Alan Koroyev]]|nat=RUS|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=78|name=[[Abdoul Gafar Sirima]]|nat=BFA|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=99|name=[[Dramane Salou]]|nat=BFA|