{"title_page": "Negative sign (astrology)", "text_new": "{{about|the [[astrology|astrological]] term|the mathematical use|Plus and minus signs}}\nIn [[western astrology|astrology]], a '''negative''', '''receptive''', '''passive''', '''yin''', '''nocturnal''' or '''feminine'''<ref>{{cite journal|last=Standen|first=Anthony|title=Is There An Astrological Effect On Personality|journal=The Journal of Psychology|date=1975|volume=89|issue=2|pages=259\u2013260|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/loi/vjrl20|accessdate=November 20, 2011|doi=10.1080/00223980.1975.9915759|pmid=1151896}}</ref> sign refers to any of the six even-numbered signs of the [[zodiac]]: [[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]], [[Cancer (astrology)|Cancer]], [[Virgo (astrology)|Virgo]], [[Scorpio (astrology)|Scorpio]], Capricorn, or [[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=van Rooij|first=Jan J. F.|title=Introversion-Extraversion: astrology versus psychology|journal=Department of Psychology, University of Leiden, the Netherlands|date=1993|volume=16|issue=6|pages=985\u2013988|doi=10.1016/0191-8869(94)90243-7}}</ref> These signs constitute the [[earth sign|earth]] and [[water sign|water]] [[triplicity|triplicities]]. You can edit whatever you want on Wikipedia. Scorpios are the greatest.\n\nNegative signs are in contrast to [[Positive sign (astrology)|positive signs]], which refer to any of the six odd-numbered signs of the zodiac and are of [[fire sign|fire]] and [[air sign|air]] triplicities: [[Aries (astrology)|Aries]], [[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]], [[Leo (astrology)|Leo]], [[Libra (astrology)|Libra]], [[Sagittarius (astrology)|Sagittarius]], and [[Aquarius (astrology)|Aquarius]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=van Rooij|first=Jan J. F.|title=Introversion-Extraversion: astrology versus psychology|journal=Department of Psychology, University of Leiden, the Netherlands|date=1993|volume=16|issue=6|pages=985\u2013988|doi=10.1016/0191-8869(94)90243-7}}</ref> The negative and positive signs\nalternate, starting with Aries as positive and Taurus as negative and continuing this pattern through the list of zodiac signs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Emerson|first=Michael|title=History of Astrology-Origins and Beginnings|url=http://www.astrology-insight.com/astrologyinformation.htm|publisher=Astrology insight|accessdate=December 5, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111202075959/http://www.astrology-insight.com/astrologyinformation.htm|archivedate=December 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Positive sign (astrology)|Positive sign]]\n* [[Triplicity]]\n* [[Earth sign]]\n* [[Water sign]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Zodiac}}\n[[Category:Western astrological signs]]\n[[Category:Negative concepts]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the [[astrology|astrological]] term|the mathematical use|Plus and minus signs}}\nIn [[western astrology|astrology]], a '''negative''', '''receptive''', '''passive''', '''yin''', '''nocturnal''' or '''feminine'''<ref>{{cite journal|last=Standen|first=Anthony|title=Is There An Astrological Effect On Personality|journal=The Journal of Psychology|date=1975|volume=89|issue=2|pages=259\u2013260|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/loi/vjrl20|accessdate=November 20, 2011|doi=10.1080/00223980.1975.9915759|pmid=1151896}}</ref> sign refers to any of the six even-numbered signs of the [[zodiac]]: [[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]], [[Cancer (astrology)|Cancer]], [[Virgo (astrology)|Virgo]], [[Scorpio (astrology)|Scorpio]], Capricorn, or [[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=van Rooij|first=Jan J. F.|title=Introversion-Extraversion: astrology versus psychology|journal=Department of Psychology, University of Leiden, the Netherlands|date=1993|volume=16|issue=6|pages=985\u2013988|doi=10.1016/0191-8869(94)90243-7}}</ref> These signs constitute the [[earth sign|earth]] and [[water sign|water]] [[triplicity|triplicities]].\n\nNegative signs are in contrast to [[Positive sign (astrology)|positive signs]], which refer to any of the six odd-numbered signs of the zodiac and are of [[fire sign|fire]] and [[air sign|air]] triplicities: [[Aries (astrology)|Aries]], [[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]], [[Leo (astrology)|Leo]], [[Libra (astrology)|Libra]], [[Sagittarius (astrology)|Sagittarius]], and [[Aquarius (astrology)|Aquarius]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=van Rooij|first=Jan J. F.|title=Introversion-Extraversion: astrology versus psychology|journal=Department of Psychology, University of Leiden, the Netherlands|date=1993|volume=16|issue=6|pages=985\u2013988|doi=10.1016/0191-8869(94)90243-7}}</ref> The negative and positive signs\nalternate, starting with Aries as positive and Taurus as negative and continuing this pattern through the list of zodiac signs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Emerson|first=Michael|title=History of Astrology-Origins and Beginnings|url=http://www.astrology-insight.com/astrologyinformation.htm|publisher=Astrology insight|accessdate=December 5, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111202075959/http://www.astrology-insight.com/astrologyinformation.htm|archivedate=December 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Positive sign (astrology)|Positive sign]]\n* [[Triplicity]]\n* [[Earth sign]]\n* [[Water sign]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Zodiac}}\n[[Category:Western astrological signs]]\n[[Category:Negative concepts]]\n", "name_user": "75.33.243.14", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed a typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negative_sign_(astrology)"}
{"title_page": "Neil Jordan", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish filmmaker and fiction writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2009}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| image        = Neil Jordan by David Shankbone.jpg\n| name         = Neil Jordan\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      = Jordan at the 2010 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|02|25}}\n| birth_place  = [[Sligo]], Ireland\n| birth_name   = Neil Patrick Jordan\n| residence    = [[Dalkey]], [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| other_names  =\n| years_active = 1979\u2013present\n| occupation   = Film director, screenwriter, novelist\n| spouse       = Vivienne Shields<br>Brenda Rawn (2004\u2013present)\n| children = 5\n}}\n'''Neil Patrick Jordan''' (born 25 February 1950) is an Irish film director, screenwriter, novelist and short-story writer. His first book, ''Night in Tunisia'', won a [[Somerset Maugham Award]] and the [[Guardian Fiction Prize]] in 1979.<ref>Duncan J. Petrie, [http://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/film-and-television-biographies/neil-jordan \"Jordan, Neil\"], Encyclopedia.com.</ref><ref>Marianne Brace, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/neil-jordan-the-writing-game-1567996.html \"Neil Jordan: the writing game\"], ''[[The Independent]]'', 14 January 1995.</ref> He won an Academy Award ([[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]) for ''[[The Crying Game]]'' (1992). He has also won three [[Irish Film and Television Awards]], as well as the [[Silver Bear for Best Director]] at the [[48th Berlin International Film Festival|Berlin International Film Festival]] for ''[[The Butcher Boy (1997 film)|The Butcher Boy]]'' (1997).<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1998/03_preistr_ger_1998/03_Preistraeger_1998.html |title=Berlinale: 1998 Prize Winners |accessdate=2012-01-15 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n\nJordan also created ''[[The Borgias (2011 TV series)|The Borgias]]'' (2011 TV series) for Showtime.\n\n==Early life==\nJordan was born in [[Sligo]], the son of Angela (n\u00e9e O'Brien), a painter, and Michael Jordan, a professor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/73/Neil-Jordan.html |title=Neil Jordan Biography (1950\u2013) |publisher=Filmreference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-02-26}}</ref> He was educated at [[St. Paul's College, Raheny]].  Later, Jordan attended [[University College Dublin]], where he studied Irish history and English literature. Of his religious background, Jordan said in a 1999 ''[[Salon Magazine|Salon]]'' interview: \"I was brought up a Catholic and was quite religious at one stage in my life, when I was young. But it left me with no scars whatever; it just sort of vanished.\" He said about his current beliefs that \"God is the greatest imaginary being of all time. Along with Einstein's [[General Theory of Relativity]], the invention of God is probably the greatest creation of human thought.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/ent/col/srag/1999/12/09/jordan/index.html|work=[[Salon.com]]|first=Michael|last=Sragow|date=9 December 1999|title=Beautiful Dreamer|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211022309/http://www.salon.com/ent/col/srag/1999/12/09/jordan/index.html|archivedate=11 February 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Film===\nWhen [[John Boorman]] was filming ''[[Excalibur (film)|Excalibur]]'' in Ireland, he recruited Jordan as a \"creative associate\". A year later Boorman was executive producer on Jordan's first feature ''[[Angel (1982 Irish film)|Angel]]'', a tale of a musician caught up in the Troubles played by [[Stephen Rea]] who has subsequently appeared in almost all of Jordan's films to date. During the 1980s, he directed films that won him acclaim, including ''[[The Company of Wolves]]'' and ''[[Mona Lisa (1986 film)|Mona Lisa]]'', both made in England. ''The Company of Wolves'', a dark and sexually-themed reimagining of the [[Little Red Riding Hood]] fairy tale based on short stories by [[Angela Carter]], became a cult favorite.\n\nAs a writer/director, Jordan has a highly idiosyncratic body of work, ranging from mainstream hits like ''[[Interview with the Vampire]]'' to commercial failures like ''[[We're No Angels (1989 film)|We're No Angels]]'' to a variety of more personal, low-budget [[arthouse]] pictures. He was also the driving force behind the cable TV series ''[[The Borgias (2011 TV series)|The Borgias]]''.\n[[File:Neil Jordan.4756.jpg|thumb|left|Neil Jordan at the German premiere of ''The Brave One'', 2007]]\n\nUnconventional sexual relationships are a recurring theme in Jordan's work, and he often finds a sympathetic side to characters that audiences would traditionally consider deviant or downright horrifying. His film ''[[The Miracle (1991 film)|The Miracle]]'', for instance, followed two characters who struggled to resist a strong, incestuous attraction. ''[[The Vampire Chronicles|Interview with the Vampire]]'', like the [[Anne Rice]] book it was based on, focused on the intense, intimate interpersonal relationship of two undead men who murder humans nightly (although the pair never have sex, they are clearly lovers of a sort), accompanied by an equally lusty vampire woman who is eternally trapped in the body of a little girl. While Lestat ([[Tom Cruise]]) is depicted in an attractive but villainous manner, his partner Louis ([[Brad Pitt]]) and the child vampire Claudia ([[Kirsten Dunst]]) are meant to capture the audience's sympathy despite their predatory nature. In the remake of ''[[The End of the Affair]]'', two people ([[Ralph Fiennes]] and [[Julianne Moore]]) engage in a love affair that will end as suddenly as it started, with both not wanting its end.\n\nIn addition to the unusual sexuality of Jordan's films, he frequently returns to the [[The Troubles|Troubles]] of [[Northern Ireland]]. ''The Crying Game'' and ''[[Breakfast on Pluto (film)|Breakfast on Pluto]]'' both concern a transgender character (played by [[Jaye Davidson]] and [[Cillian Murphy]], respectively), both concern the Troubles, and both feature frequent Jordan leading man Stephen Rea. The two films, however, are very different, with ''Crying Game'' being a realistic thriller/romance and ''Breakfast on Pluto'' a much more episodic, stylized, darkly comic biography. Jordan also frequently tells stories about children or young people, such as ''The Miracle'' and ''[[The Butcher Boy (1997 film)|The Butcher Boy]]''. While his pictures are most often grounded in reality, he occasionally directs more fantastic or dreamlike films, such as ''[[The Company of Wolves]]'', ''[[High Spirits (film)|High Spirits]],'' ''Interview with the Vampire''  and ''[[In Dreams (film)|In Dreams]]''.\n\n[[File:Alicja Bachleda, Colin Farrell & Neil Jordan by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|right|Jordan with [[Alicja Bachleda-Curu\u015b]] and [[Colin Farrell]] at the ''[[Ondine (film)|Ondine]]'' premiere, 2010 Tribeca Film Festival in New York]]\nThe critical success of Jordan's early pictures led him to Hollywood, where he directed ''[[High Spirits (film)|High Spirits]]'' and ''[[We're No Angels (1989 film)|We're No Angels]]''; both were critical and financial disasters. He later returned home to make the more personal ''[[The Crying Game]]'', which was nominated for six Academy Awards. Jordan won the [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay]] for the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1993/?|title=The 65th Academy Awards {{!}} 1993|work=Oscars.org {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|access-date=2018-12-04|language=en}}</ref> Its unexpected success led him back to American studio filmmaking, where he directed ''[[Interview with the Vampire (film)|Interview with the Vampire]]''. He also directed the crime drama ''[[The Brave One (2007 film)|The Brave One]]'' starring Jodie Foster.\n\nNeil Gaiman announced during his ''The Today Show'' appearance on 27 January 2009, that Neil Jordan would be directing the film of his Newbery Medal-winning book ''The Graveyard Book''. Jordan also wrote and directed the Irish made film ''[[Ondine (film)|Ondine]]'' (2009), starring [[Colin Farrell]] and [[Alicja Bachleda-Curu\u015b]]. He also directed ''[[Byzantium (film)|Byzantium]]'', an adaptation of the vampire play of the same name starring [[Saoirse Ronan]], [[Gemma Arterton]] and [[Jonny Lee Miller]].<ref name=byzantium>{{cite web|title=Saoirse Ronan and Gemma Arterton to Star in Vampire Pic 'Byzantium' (Cannes) |url= http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/saoirse-ronan-gemma-arterton-star-188454 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first = Stuart |last=Kemp |date=14 May 2011 |accessdate=15 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Jordan's next feature was announced as ''Broken Dream'' and featured [[Ben Kingsley]] and [[John Hurt]].<ref name=\"Broken Dream\">{{cite web|url=http://iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4283808&tpl=archnews&force=1|title=Ben Kinglsey & John Hurt for Neil Jordan - John Boorman's 'Broken Dream' |publisher=IFTN |accessdate=15 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nMost recently, he directed the thriller ''[[Greta (2018 film)|Greta]]'' (2018), starring [[Isabelle Huppert]] and [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nJordan has five children: Anna and Sarah from his marriage to solicitor Vivienne Shields; Dashiel and deejGay Jordan from his current marriage to Brenda Rawn, and Ben, from a relationship with architect Mary Donohoe.\n\nJordan lives in a house in [[Dalkey]], a heritage village near [[D\u00fan Laoghaire]], within the southern suburbs of [[Dublin]].<ref>[http://www.dublintourist.com/towns/dalkey/ Famous People of Dalkey']</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Neil Jordan was honoured with receiving the French [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] <ref>Ordre des Arts et des Lettres</ref>\n\nHe has received many honorary doctorates, most notably from [[Trinity College Dublin]], [[University College Dublin]], and [[Queen's University Belfast]].<ref>http://www.ucd.ie/news/june05/jordancitation.htm</ref><ref>https://www.tcd.ie/news_events/articles/film-director-neil-jordan-among-recipients-of-honorary-degrees-at-tcd-2/</ref><ref>https://www.qub.ac.uk/about/Leadership-and-structure/Registrars-Office/FileStore/Filetoupload,837203,en.pdf</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he signed a petition in support of director [[Roman Polanski]], calling for his release after he was arrested in Switzerland in relation to his [[Roman Polanski sexual abuse case|1977 charge for drugging and raping a 13-year-old girl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://laregledujeu.org/2009/11/10/479/signez-la-petition-pour-roman-polanski/|title=Signez la p\u00e9tition pour Roman Polanski !|publisher=La R\u00e8gle du jeu|language=French|date=10 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/regionals/braypeople/news/sinead-demands-jordan-remove-name-from-polanski-petition-27632281.html|title=Sinead demands Jordan remove name from Polanski petition|website=Independent.ie|date=13 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he has donated his archives to the [[National Library of Ireland]]. Jordan's donation included TV and film scripts, production files, notebooks, storyboards and personal correspondence with artists and political figures.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/neil-jordan-donates-vast-archive-to-national-library-of-ireland-1.3590879|title=Neil Jordan donates \u2018vast\u2019 archive to National Library of Ireland|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-12-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! width=\"60\"| [[Film director|Director]]\n! width=\"60\"| [[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=\"60\"| [[Film producer|Producer]]\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Angel (1982 Irish film)|Angel]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[The Company of Wolves]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Mona Lisa (1986 film)|Mona Lisa]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| Nominated- [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction]]<br>Nominated- [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay]]<br>Nominated- [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay]]\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[High Spirits (film)|High Spirits]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[We're No Angels (1989 film)|We're No Angels]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[The Miracle (1991 film)|The Miracle]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[The Crying Game]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay]]<br>Nominated- [[Academy Award for Best Director]]<br>Nominated- [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction]]<br>Nominated- [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay]]\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Interview with the Vampire (film)|Interview with the Vampire]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| Nominated- [[Saturn Award for Best Director]]\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Michael Collins (film)|Michael Collins]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| [[Golden Lion]]\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[The Butcher Boy (1997 film)|The Butcher Boy]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|executive}}\n| [[Silver Bear for Best Director]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1999\n| ''[[The End of the Affair (1999 film)|The End of the Affair]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]]<br>Nominated- [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction]]<br>Nominated- [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director]]\n|-\n| ''[[In Dreams (film)|In Dreams]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Beckett on Film#Not I|Not I]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[The Good Thief (film)|The Good Thief]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|executive}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2003\n| ''[[The Actors]]''\n| {{no}}\n| {{partial|story}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Intermission (film)|Intermission]]''\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Breakfast on Pluto (film)|Breakfast on Pluto]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[The Brave One (2007 film)|The Brave One]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Ondine (film)|Ondine]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Byzantium (film)|Byzantium]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Greta (2018 film)|Greta]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n'''Executive producer only'''\n* ''The Courier'' (1988)\n* ''[[The Last September (film)|The Last September]]'' (1999)\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! width=\"60\"| Director\n! width=\"60\"| Writer\n! width=\"60\"| Executive<br>Producer\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2011\u20132013\n| ''[[The Borgias (2011 TV series)|The Borgias]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|rowspan=2| Creator\n|-\n| 2017\u2013\n| ''[[Riviera (TV series)|Riviera]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|- \n|}\n\n==Fiction==\n* ''Night in Tunisia'' (1976, short stories)\n* ''The Past'' (1980)\n* ''The Dream of a Beast'' (1983)\n* ''Sunrise with Sea Monster'' (1994) published in the USA as \u2018\u2019Nightlines\u2019\u2019\n* ''[[Shade (novel)|Shade]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Mistaken (novel)|Mistaken]]'' (2011)\n* ''The Drowned Detective'' (2016)\n* ''Carnivalesque'' (2017)<ref>[http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/carnivalesque-review-neil-jordan-s-cirque-du-supernatural-1.2965586 \"Carnivalesque review: Neil Jordan\u2019s cirque du supernatural\"]. Irish Times.</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n* [[Guardian Fiction Prize]] and [[Somerset Maugham Award]] for ''Night in Tunisia'' (1979)\n* [[Rooney Prize for Irish Literature]] in 1981 <ref>\"Neil Jordan Gets Rooney Prize\", The Irish Times, 7 October 1981</ref>\n* 2004 [[Irish PEN Award]]\n* [[Kerry Group Irish Fiction Award]] for 'Shade' (2005) and Mistaken (2011) <ref>\"Kerry Group Irish Fiction Award \u2013 Literary Competitions \u2013 39th Listowel Writers' Week 2009\". Listowel Writers' Week. Archived from the original on 23 March 2012. Retrieved 23 September 2011.</ref><ref>C\u00edan Nihill (2 June 2011). \"Neil Jordan wins major literary award for second time\". The Irish Times. Retrieved 23 September 2011.</ref>\n* 2011 [[Irish Book Awards]] Novel of the Year for 'Mistaken'<ref>Ronan McGreevy (18 November 2011). \"Heaney honoured at book awards\". The Irish Times. Retrieved 25 October 2012.</ref>\n\n==Awards received by Jordan movies==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Film\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Academy Awards\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| BAFTA Awards\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Golden Globe Awards\n|-\n! Nominations\n! Wins\n! Nominations\n! Wins\n! Nominations\n! Wins\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[The Company of Wolves]]''\n|\n|\n|align=center|4\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Mona Lisa (1986 film)|Mona Lisa]]''\n|align=center|1\n|\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|1\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[The Crying Game]]''\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|1\n|\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Interview with the Vampire (film)|Interview with the Vampire]]''\n|align=center|2\n|\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|2\n|\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Michael Collins (film)|Michael Collins]]''\n|align=center|2\n|\n|align=center|2\n|\n|align=center|2\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[The End of the Affair (1999 film)|The End of the Affair]]'' \n|align=center|2\n|\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|4\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Breakfast on Pluto (film)|Breakfast on Pluto]]'' \n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[The Brave One (2007 film)|The Brave One]]''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|'''Total'''\n!align=center|13\n!align=center|1\n!align=center|33\n!align=center|5\n!align=center|15\n!align=center|1\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Neil Jordan}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051028075930/http://www.neiljordan.com/ Neil Jordan's web site]\n* {{IMDb name|0001403}}\n* [http://www.futuremovies.co.uk/filmmaking/neil-jordan/johan-de-silva Neil Jordan \"Breakfast On Pluto\"] Interview\n\n{{Neil Jordan}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Neil Jordan\n|list  = \n{{AcademyAwardBestOriginalScreenplay 1981\u20132000}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay 1983\u20131999}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for Director of the Year}}\n{{Rooney Prize for Irish Literature}}\n{{Silver Bear for Best Director}}\n{{Writers Guild of America Award for Best Original Screenplay}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jordan, Neil}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Clontarf]]\n[[Category:People from Dalkey]]\n[[Category:People from County Sligo]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Paul's College, Raheny]]\n[[Category:Aosd\u00e1na members]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Best Original Screenplay Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Irish atheists]]\n[[Category:Irish film directors]]\n[[Category:Irish novelists]]\n[[Category:Irish screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Irish male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Directors of Golden Lion winners]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for Best Director recipients]]\n[[Category:Writers Guild of America Award winners]]\n[[Category:Irish PEN Award for Literature winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish male writers]]\n[[Category:Irish male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century short story writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish filmmaker and fiction writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2009}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| image        = Neil Jordan by David Shankbone.jpg\n| name         = Neil Jordan\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      = Jordan at the 2010 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|02|25}}\n| birth_place  = [[Sligo]], Ireland\n| birth_name   = Neil Patrick Jordan\n| residence    = [[Dalkey]], [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| other_names  =\n| years_active = 1979\u2013present\n| occupation   = Film director, screenwriter, novelist\n| spouse       = Vivienne Shields<br>Brenda Rawn (2004\u2013present)\n| children = 5\n}}\n'''Neil Patrick Jordan''' (born 25 February 1950) is an Irish film director, screenwriter, novelist and short-story writer. His first book, ''Night in Tunisia'', won a [[Somerset Maugham Award]] and the [[Guardian Fiction Prize]] in 1979.<ref>Duncan J. Petrie, [http://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/film-and-television-biographies/neil-jordan \"Jordan, Neil\"], Encyclopedia.com.</ref><ref>Marianne Brace, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/neil-jordan-the-writing-game-1567996.html \"Neil Jordan: the writing game\"], ''[[The Independent]]'', 14 January 1995.</ref> He won an Academy Award ([[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]) for ''[[The Crying Game]]'' (1992). He has also won three [[Irish Film and Television Awards]], as well as the [[Silver Bear for Best Director]] at the [[48th Berlin International Film Festival|Berlin International Film Festival]] for ''[[The Butcher Boy (1997 film)|The Butcher Boy]]'' (1997).<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1998/03_preistr_ger_1998/03_Preistraeger_1998.html |title=Berlinale: 1998 Prize Winners |accessdate=2012-01-15 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n\nJordan also created ''[[The Borgias (2011 TV series)|The Borgias]]'' (2011 TV series) for Showtime.\n\n==Early life==\nJordan was born in [[Sligo]], the son of Angela (n\u00e9e O'Brien), a painter, and Michael Jordan, a professor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/73/Neil-Jordan.html |title=Neil Jordan Biography (1950\u2013) |publisher=Filmreference.com |date= |accessdate=2013-02-26}}</ref> He was educated at [[St. Paul's College, Raheny]].  Later, Jordan attended [[University College Dublin]], where he studied Irish history and English literature. Of his religious background, Jordan said in a 1999 ''[[Salon Magazine|Salon]]'' interview: \"I was brought up a Catholic and was quite religious at one stage in my life, when I was young. But it left me with no scars whatever; it just sort of vanished.\" He said about his current beliefs that \"God is the greatest imaginary being of all time. Along with Einstein's [[General Theory of Relativity]], the invention of God is probably the greatest creation of human thought.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/ent/col/srag/1999/12/09/jordan/index.html|work=[[Salon.com]]|first=Michael|last=Sragow|date=9 December 1999|title=Beautiful Dreamer|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211022309/http://www.salon.com/ent/col/srag/1999/12/09/jordan/index.html|archivedate=11 February 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Film===\nWhen [[John Boorman]] was filming ''[[Excalibur (film)|Excalibur]]'' in Ireland, he recruited Jordan as a \"creative associate\". A year later Boorman was executive producer on Jordan's first feature ''[[Angel (1982 Irish film)|Angel]]'', a tale of a musician caught up in the Troubles played by [[Stephen Rea]] who has subsequently appeared in almost all of Jordan's films to date. During the 1980s, he directed films that won him acclaim, including ''[[The Company of Wolves]]'' and ''[[Mona Lisa (1986 film)|Mona Lisa]]'', both made in England. ''The Company of Wolves'', a dark and sexually-themed reimagining of the [[Little Red Riding Hood]] fairy tale based on short stories by [[Angela Carter]], became a cult favorite.\n\nAs a writer/director, Jordan has a highly idiosyncratic body of work, ranging from mainstream hits like ''[[Interview with the Vampire]]'' to commercial failures like ''[[We're No Angels (1989 film)|We're No Angels]]'' to a variety of more personal, low-budget [[arthouse]] pictures. He was also the driving force behind the cable TV series ''[[The Borgias (2011 TV series)|The Borgias]]''.\n[[File:Neil Jordan.4756.jpg|thumb|left|Neil Jordan at the German premiere of ''The Brave One'', 2007]]\n\nUnconventional sexual relationships are a recurring theme in Jordan's work, and he often finds a sympathetic side to characters that audiences would traditionally consider deviant or downright horrifying. His film ''[[The Miracle (1991 film)|The Miracle]]'', for instance, followed two characters who struggled to resist a strong, incestuous attraction. ''[[The Vampire Chronicles|Interview with the Vampire]]'', like the [[Anne Rice]] book it was based on, focused on the intense, intimate interpersonal relationship of two undead men who murder humans nightly (although the pair never have sex, they are clearly lovers of a sort), accompanied by an equally lusty vampire woman who is eternally trapped in the body of a little girl. While Lestat ([[Tom Cruise]]) is depicted in an attractive but villainous manner, his partner Louis ([[Brad Pitt]]) and the child vampire Claudia ([[Kirsten Dunst]]) are meant to capture the audience's sympathy despite their predatory nature. In the remake of ''[[The End of the Affair]]'', two people ([[Ralph Fiennes]] and [[Julianne Moore]]) engage in a love affair that will end as suddenly as it started, with both not wanting its end.\n\nIn addition to the unusual sexuality of Jordan's films, he frequently returns to the [[The Troubles|Troubles]] of [[Northern Ireland]]. ''The Crying Game'' and ''[[Breakfast on Pluto (film)|Breakfast on Pluto]]'' both concern a transgender character (played by [[Jaye Davidson]] and [[Cillian Murphy]], respectively), both concern the Troubles, and both feature frequent Jordan leading man Stephen Rea. The two films, however, are very different, with ''Crying Game'' being a realistic thriller/romance and ''Breakfast on Pluto'' a much more episodic, stylized, darkly comic biography. Jordan also frequently tells stories about children or young people, such as ''The Miracle'' and ''[[The Butcher Boy (1997 film)|The Butcher Boy]]''. While his pictures are most often grounded in reality, he occasionally directs more fantastic or dreamlike films, such as ''[[The Company of Wolves]]'', ''[[High Spirits (film)|High Spirits]],'' ''Interview with the Vampire''  and ''[[In Dreams (film)|In Dreams]]''.\n\n[[File:Alicja Bachleda, Colin Farrell & Neil Jordan by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|right|Jordan with [[Alicja Bachleda-Curu\u015b]] and [[Colin Farrell]] at the ''[[Ondine (film)|Ondine]]'' premiere, 2010 Tribeca Film Festival in New York]]\nThe critical success of Jordan's early pictures led him to Hollywood, where he directed ''[[High Spirits (film)|High Spirits]]'' and ''[[We're No Angels (1989 film)|We're No Angels]]''; both were critical and financial disasters. He later returned home to make the more personal ''[[The Crying Game]]'', which was nominated for six Academy Awards. Jordan won the [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay]] for the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1993/?|title=The 65th Academy Awards {{!}} 1993|work=Oscars.org {{!}} Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|access-date=2018-12-04|language=en}}</ref> Its unexpected success led him back to American studio filmmaking, where he directed ''[[Interview with the Vampire (film)|Interview with the Vampire]]''. He also directed the crime drama ''[[The Brave One (2007 film)|The Brave One]]'' starring Jodie Foster.\n\nNeil Gaiman announced during his ''The Today Show'' appearance on 27 January 2009, that Neil Jordan would be directing the film of his Newbery Medal-winning book ''The Graveyard Book''. Jordan also wrote and directed the Irish made film ''[[Ondine (film)|Ondine]]'' (2009), starring [[Colin Farrell]] and [[Alicja Bachleda-Curu\u015b]]. He also directed ''[[Byzantium (film)|Byzantium]]'', an adaptation of the vampire play of the same name starring [[Saoirse Ronan]], [[Gemma Arterton]] and [[Jonny Lee Miller]].<ref name=byzantium>{{cite web|title=Saoirse Ronan and Gemma Arterton to Star in Vampire Pic 'Byzantium' (Cannes) |url= http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/saoirse-ronan-gemma-arterton-star-188454 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first = Stuart |last=Kemp |date=14 May 2011 |accessdate=15 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Jordan's next feature was announced as ''Broken Dream'' and featured [[Ben Kingsley]] and [[John Hurt]].<ref name=\"Broken Dream\">{{cite web|url=http://iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4283808&tpl=archnews&force=1|title=Ben Kinglsey & John Hurt for Neil Jordan - John Boorman's 'Broken Dream' |publisher=IFTN |accessdate=15 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nMost recently, he directed the thriller ''[[Greta (2018 film)|Greta]]'' (2018), starring [[Isabelle Huppert]] and [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nJordan has five children: Anna and Sarah from his marriage to solicitor Vivienne Shields; Dashiel and deejGay Jordan from his current marriage to Brenda Rawn, and Ben, from a relationship with architect Mary Donohoe.\n\nJordan lives in a house in [[Dalkey]], a heritage village near [[D\u00fan Laoghaire]], within the southern suburbs of [[Dublin]].<ref>[http://www.dublintourist.com/towns/dalkey/ Famous People of Dalkey']</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Neil Jordan was honoured with receiving the French [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] <ref>Ordre des Arts et des Lettres</ref>\n\nHe has received many honorary doctorates, most notably from [[Trinity College Dublin]], [[University College Dublin]], and [[Queen's University Belfast]].<ref>http://www.ucd.ie/news/june05/jordancitation.htm</ref><ref>https://www.tcd.ie/news_events/articles/film-director-neil-jordan-among-recipients-of-honorary-degrees-at-tcd-2/</ref><ref>https://www.qub.ac.uk/about/Leadership-and-structure/Registrars-Office/FileStore/Filetoupload,837203,en.pdf</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he signed a petition in support of director [[Roman Polanski]], calling for his release after he was arrested in Switzerland in relation to his [[Roman Polanski sexual abuse case|1977 charge for drugging and raping a 13-year-old girl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://laregledujeu.org/2009/11/10/479/signez-la-petition-pour-roman-polanski/|title=Signez la p\u00e9tition pour Roman Polanski !|publisher=La R\u00e8gle du jeu|language=French|date=10 November 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/regionals/braypeople/news/sinead-demands-jordan-remove-name-from-polanski-petition-27632281.html|title=Sinead demands Jordan remove name from Polanski petition|website=Independent.ie|date=13 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he has donated his archives to the [[National Library of Ireland]]. Jordan's donation included TV and film scripts, production files, notebooks, storyboards and personal correspondence with artists and political figures.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/neil-jordan-donates-vast-archive-to-national-library-of-ireland-1.3590879|title=Neil Jordan donates \u2018vast\u2019 archive to National Library of Ireland|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-12-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! width=\"60\"| [[Film director|Director]]\n! width=\"60\"| [[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=\"60\"| [[Film producer|Producer]]\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Angel (1982 Irish film)|Angel]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[The Company of Wolves]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Mona Lisa (1986 film)|Mona Lisa]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| Nominated- [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction]]<br>Nominated- [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay]]<br>Nominated- [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay]]\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[High Spirits (film)|High Spirits]]